#compdef falcon
# =============================================================================
# falcon — Giancarlo Niccolai's "Falcon Programming Language" — a
#          multi-paradigm scripting language designed from the
#          ground up to combine SIX distinct programming paradigms
#          in a single language + runtime: imperative, prototype-
#          oriented OOP, functional, statement-oriented, tabular,
#          and message-passing.  Distinguishing from every other
#          documented language by:
#            - SIX-PARADIGM FUSION — Falcon programs can freely
#              mix imperative blocks, OOP class hierarchies (with
#              prototype-style inheritance), pure functional
#              expressions, statement-oriented control flow, table-
#              oriented data manipulation, and message-passing
#              concurrency primitives WITHIN A SINGLE FILE
#            - SOURCE→.fam→VM EXECUTION MODEL — Falcon sources
#              compile to .fam (Falcon Assembled Module) bytecode
#              files (-c flag), which the VM (`falcon -x`) loads
#              + executes; the default `falcon module.fal`
#              compiles + runs in one step with auto-caching
#            - FTD (Falcon Template Documents) — `-T` flag enables
#              templating mode where the module is treated as a
#              text-with-embedded-code document (like PHP/ERB);
#              useful for web view generation
#            - INTERACTIVE LISTENER via `-i` — full Falcon REPL
#              with `-p <module>` preload (pump-in) of modules
#              into the listener namespace
#            - 5 EXECUTION MODES via "modal options" (mutually
#              exclusive):
#                * default: compile + run
#                * -c: compile to .fam only (no run)
#                * -i: interactive listener
#                * -S: produce assembly output (debug)
#                * -t: produce syntactic tree output
#                * -y: write string translation table
#                * -x: execute compiled .fam binary
#                * --cgi: CGI-mode execution
#            - PRELOAD-IN-VM SUPPORT via `-p <module>` —
#              repeatable; useful in interactive mode + CGI
#            - SEPARATE COMPILATION + RUN-TIME OPTIONS — `c_opts`
#              control compilation (memory mode, encoding,
#              force-recompile, FTD mode); `r_opts` control
#              execution (memory checking, encoding, language,
#              load path, save-modules behavior)
#            - SEMICOLON-SEPARATED PATH SYNTAX — Falcon paths
#              use forward-slash separators + semicolon list
#              entries (`/usr/local/falcon;/opt/falcon`); leading
#              `;` removes standard system paths
#          Used by: language-paradigm researchers + scripting-
#          language enthusiasts exploring fusion designs + as a
#          reference for embedded-scripting use in C++ apps.
#
# Author:  Giancarlo Niccolai (giancarloniccolai on GitHub +
#          falconpl on GitHub organization) — Italian software
#          architect, started Falcon in 2003 as a scripting
#          language unifying paradigms.  Falcon 1 (falconpl/
#          falcon) maintains the classic design through 2026;
#          Falcon 2 (falconpl/Falcon2) is the new incarnation.
#          License: GPLv2 (Falcon 1).
# Source:  https://github.com/falconpl/falcon
#          https://github.com/falconpl/falcon/blob/master/clt/falcon/options.cpp
#          https://github.com/falconpl/Falcon2 (new Falcon 2)
#          https://falconpl.org/ (project home, status TBD)
# CLI:     clt/falcon/options.cpp — hand-rolled C++ argument
#          parser walking argv with switch-case on the second
#          character of each argument (`op[1]`).  Supports
#          adjacent option-value syntax (-o<file>) and space-
#          separated syntax (-o <file>).
# Language: FALCON
#           ("Falcon" — Giancarlo Niccolai — released 2003 as
#            a "multi-paradigm scripting language".  Distinct
#            from every previously-documented language by:
#              1. SIX-PARADIGM FUSION — imperative + prototype-
#                 OOP + functional + statement-oriented +
#                 tabular + message-passing.  No other documented
#                 language explicitly designs for six paradigms;
#                 most fuse 2-3 (e.g. Logtalk R612 fuses OOP +
#                 logic; Ioke R636 fuses prototype-OOP + Lisp +
#                 message-passing)
#              2. .fam (Falcon Assembled Module) BYTECODE FORMAT
#                 — compiled bytecode files that the VM loads;
#                 design predates LLVM IR / GraalVM truffle / etc.
#              3. FTD TEMPLATE-DOCUMENT MODE — built-in mode for
#                 text-with-embedded-code documents, eliminating
#                 the need for an external template engine
#              4. TABULAR DATA PARADIGM as first-class — Falcon's
#                 "tabular" paradigm provides primitives for
#                 row-oriented operations on collections,
#                 distinct from list-oriented functional paradigm
#                 vs imperative array iteration
#              5. STATEMENT-ORIENTED PARADIGM — distinct
#                 designation for top-level statements + sequential
#                 control flow as a "paradigm" separate from
#                 imperative (which has more rigid block structure)
#              6. MESSAGE-PASSING CONCURRENCY — built-in primitives
#                 inspired by Erlang/Smalltalk but adapted to
#                 scripting use cases
#              7. NICCOLAI / FALCONPL ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE —
#                 Giancarlo Niccolai has continuously maintained
#                 Falcon since 2003 (23 years); founded the
#                 falconpl organization on GitHub which hosts
#                 Falcon 1 + Falcon 2 + various Falcon-related
#                 tools)
# License: GPLv2 (Falcon 1.x)
# Status:  Falcon 1 — 68+ stars on falconpl/falcon, slow but
#          continuous development through 2026.  Falcon 2 — 41+
#          stars on falconpl/Falcon2, active rewrite/evolution
#          of the original design.  Niche academic interest +
#          paradigm-fusion research projects.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 92ND LANGUAGE DOCUMENTED
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its **92ND PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: Falcon.  This expands the taxonomy
# from 91 to 92 languages, joining the prior 91 in the cross-language
# inventory.  Taxonomy now spans 379 cross-language CLI library variants
# across **92 documented languages**.
#
# Pattern: R637 Rust=67 (camino — Axis 14 OPENS) → R638 Go=67 (afero) →
# R639 TS-Node=67 (fast-glob — Axis 14 reaches 1/1/1) → R640 92ND
# LANGUAGE (Falcon THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-bump + new-
# language segment.  Expected R641 begins next segment (likely Rust=68
# → Go=68 → TS-Node=68 → 93rd language).
#
# Leaderboard unchanged at R640: Rust=67, Go=67, TypeScript-Node=67
# (three-way tie at 67).
#
# WHY FALCON IS A DISTINCTIVE 92ND LANGUAGE:
#
# Falcon occupies a unique cell in the language design space that NO
# previously-documented language fully fills:
#
#   Feature              | Falcon    | Other documented langs
#   ---------------------|-----------|------------------------
#   Six-paradigm fusion  | ✓ all 6   | Most documented langs
#   (imperative + proto-   in single   fuse 2-3 paradigms
#   OOP + functional +     language    (Logtalk R612 = OOP+logic;
#   statement-oriented +                 Ioke R636 = OOP+Lisp+msg;
#   tabular + message-                   Curry/Mercury = FP+logic;
#   passing)                             ATS R605 = FP+linear+dep)
#   .fam BYTECODE        | ✓ since   | Most have bytecode but
#   intermediate format    2003        Falcon's .fam predates
#                                       GraalVM truffle (2014)
#                                       and LLVM bitcode-as-IR
#   FTD template-        | ✓ -T flag | None — most use separate
#   document mode                       template engines (Jinja,
#                                       ERB, Handlebars, etc.)
#   Tabular paradigm     | ✓ first-  | None — most have list/
#   as first-class         class        array as primitive but not
#                                       "tabular paradigm" as a
#                                       distinct concept
#   23-YEAR SINGLE-      | ✓ 2003-   | Many fit, but Falcon is
#   AUTHOR DEVELOPMENT     2026        sustained single-author
#                                       (Giancarlo Niccolai)
#
# Falcon's six paradigms in detail:
#   1. IMPERATIVE — variables, assignments, loops, blocks
#   2. PROTOTYPE-OOP — objects derived from prototypes (similar
#      to Self R581, JavaScript)
#   3. FUNCTIONAL — first-class functions, closures, higher-order
#      operations
#   4. STATEMENT-ORIENTED — top-level scripts, sequential control
#      flow, statement-as-expression style
#   5. TABULAR — row-oriented operations on collection-of-records
#      data structures; SQL-style projections + filters as
#      language primitives
#   6. MESSAGE-PASSING — concurrent primitives for inter-process
#      communication via messages
#
# Cross-language analogs (closest matches by feature combination):
#   - Multi-paradigm scripting → Python (imperative + FP + OOP +
#                                  some functional)
#   - Multi-paradigm + bytecode → Ruby (similar)
#   - Six-paradigm explicit → no direct analog
#   - Template-document mode → PHP (similar PHP-style)
#   - Tabular as paradigm → R, SAS (statistical languages)
#
# Falcon is the FIRST documented language with EXPLICIT SIX-PARADIGM
# FUSION (imperative + prototype-OOP + functional + statement-
# oriented + tabular + message-passing) as its primary design
# thesis.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
